FEWSHOT_EXAMPLES = ['Input:\n<<<\nIn conclusion, this framework provides a robust path forward. Furthermore, it is important to note that future work may improve accuracy, though we would like to note that our work is not necessarily dependent on such improvements.\n>>>\n>>>\nOutput:\n<span>In <span>conclusion<annotation type="AI" why="a standard closing phrase AI reuses across nearly every summary it generates" score="0.8" /></span>, this framework provides a <span>robust path forward<annotation type="AI" why="strong claim with no supporting detail — AI tends to close sections with confident-sounding phrases that don\'t commit to specifics" score="0.6" /></span>. <span>Furthermore<annotation type="AI" why="AI often chains sentences with \'Furthermore\' to keep going without actually advancing the argument" score="0.7" /></span>, it is important to note that <span>future work <span>may<annotation type="human" why="\'may\' softens the promise just enough that it cannot be held to it" score="0.3" /></span> improve accuracy<annotation type="AI" why="pointing to future work is a common AI way of acknowledging limitations without admitting them directly" score="0.6" /></span>, though <span>we<annotation type="human" why="\'we\' is the one word here that anchors this in real people rather than an impersonal document voice" score="0.3" /></span> would like to note that <span>our work is not necessarily dependent on such improvements<annotation type="human" why="the double negative \'not necessarily dependent\' cancels itself out — no real claim is being made" score="0.3" /></span>.<annotation type="AI" why="polished academic structure with stacked transition phrases and vague forward-looking statements" score="0.7" /></span>\n', 'Input:\n<<<\nI met her at Howth Rd Stn, we talked for 5 mins, then I relized I had the wrong ticket.\n>>>\n>>>\nOutput:\n<span>I met her at <span>Howth Rd Stn<annotation type="human" why="a real train station in Dublin — a specific place only someone familiar with it would name" score="0.8" /></span>, we talked for <span>5 mins<annotation type="human" why="casual abbreviation instead of \'minutes\' — the kind of shorthand people use when writing quickly" score="0.6" /></span>, then I <span>relized<annotation type="human" why="spelling mistake that suggests fast, unedited typing" score="0.9" /></span> I had the wrong ticket.<annotation type="human" why="specific local knowledge, casual shorthand, and an unedited typo all point to genuine human writing" score="0.8" /></span>\n', 'Input:\n<<<\n1) gather data 2) clean it 3) run model 4) report results, easy.\n>>>\n>>>\nOutput:\n<span><span>1) gather data 2) clean it 3) run model 4) report results<annotation type="AI" why="four steps compressed into one line with no explanation between them — a list format AI reaches for rather than narrating the process" score="0.7" /></span>, <span>easy.<annotation type="human" why="the dry \'easy.\' at the end undercuts the list — a wry human aside rather than a planned conclusion" score="0.7" /></span><annotation type="AI" why="compressed list structure typical of AI, though the wry closing word breaks the pattern" score="0.55" /></span>\n', 'Input:\n<<<\nThis analysis is nuanced, and both perspectives have merit; however, the final decision depends on context.\n>>>\n>>>\nOutput:\n<span>This analysis is <span>nuanced, and both perspectives have merit<annotation type="AI" why="AI frequently uses this structure — acknowledge both sides, then immediately pivot — as a way to appear balanced without taking a position" score="0.75" /></span>; however, the final decision <span>depends on context<annotation type="AI" why="\'depends on context\' without specifying any context — a phrase that sounds considered while saying nothing" score="0.8" /></span>.<annotation type="AI" why="classic AI balance-pivot structure with a vague context-dependent conclusion" score="0.8" /></span>\n', 'Input:\n<<<\nNo way!! I finally fixed the fucking unity meta quest oom bug after like three lucozades and one (or two!!!) terrible ideas, deadass this is a W\n>>>\n>>>\nOutput:\n<span><span>No way<span>!!<annotation type="human" why="I think AI is more likely to write just one exclamation mark since that appears in training data more often" score="0.7" /></span><annotation type="human" why="starting with \'No way\' seems very desperate and emotional, AI tends to be more aseptic" score="0.8" /></span> I <span>finally<annotation type="human" why="the writer really seems to be very desperate" score="0.5" /></span> fixed the <span>fucking<annotation type="human" why="swearing is not common in AI writing because it\'s trained to be polite and professional" score="0.85" /></span> <span>unity meta quest oom bug<annotation type="human" why="this is a very specific technical bug name that only makes sense if you have actually worked on this, AI would probably have a more generic error like \'404 error\'" score="0.8" /></span> after <span>like three <span>lucozades<annotation type="human" why="Lucozade is a UK/Ireland energy drink, which tells us the writer has a specific cultural background, and AI generally uses more generic brands like \'Coca-Cola\'" score="0.8" /></span><annotation type="human" why="this is very casual, AI tends to be more formal" score="0.6" /></span> and one <span>(or two<span>!!!<annotation type="human" why="three exclamation marks now, this is very emotional and intense" score="0.6" /></span>)<annotation type="human" why="this sounds like a second thought after writing the text, and AI can\'t go back and edit it" score="0.65" /></span> <span>terrible ideas<annotation type="human" why="mocking your own ideas means you have some self-awareness to look back and judge yourself" score="0.6" /></span>, <span>deadass<annotation type="human" why="this is a big inconsistency, if the writer is UK/Ireland, they\'d say \'honestly\' or \'no word of a lie\' instead of American slang like this" score="0.7" /></span> this is a <span>W<annotation type="human" why="another inconsistency (maybe the writer has a mixed background?), this is American gaming slang meaning \'win\', UK/Ireland people would more likely say \'class\' or \'mental win\'" score="0.65" /></span><annotation type="human" why="casual language, swearing, specific local references, and inconsistent slang patterns — too messy to be AI" score="0.85" /></span>\n', 'Input:\n<<<\nThe implementation demonstrates scalability, interpretability, and adaptability across domains. Would you like me to explain each point?\n>>>\n>>>\nOutput:\n<span>The implementation demonstrates <span>scalability, interpretability, and adaptability<annotation type="AI" why="three abstract technical qualities listed together — each interchangeable with the others, none grounded in what the implementation actually does" score="0.8" /></span> across <span>domains<annotation type="AI" why="\'across domains\' claims universal applicability without naming a single domain" score="0.7" /></span>. <span>Would you like me to explain each point?<annotation type="AI" why="an offer to continue explaining — the reflex of a chat assistant, not how a statement ends" score="0.95" /></span><annotation type="AI" why="abstract quality list and a classic assistant sign-off — textbook AI artifacts" score="0.9" /></span>\n', 'Input:\n<<<\nThe cat sat on the keyboard and now my terminal says asdf and I literally cant stop laughing lololol\n>>>\n>>>\nOutput:\n<span><span>The cat sat on the<annotation type="AI" why="a person telling this story would describe the cat somehow — AI moves straight to the punchline without the human texture" score="0.6" /></span> keyboard and now my terminal says <span>asdf<annotation type="AI" why="too orderly — a cat randomly walking on a keyboard would produce something less regular than \'asdf\'" score="0.7" /></span> and I <span>literally<annotation type="human" why="\'literally\' used for comic effect rather than literally — a spoken English habit AI tends to avoid" score="0.55" /></span> <span>cant<annotation type="human" why="missing apostrophe, the kind of typo from fast typing" score="0.75" /></span> stop laughing <span>lololol<annotation type="human" why="the repeated letters extend with the emotion — people naturally write \'lol\' longer when they find something funnier" score="0.8" /></span><annotation type="AI" why="the orderly \'asdf\' and bland opening are AI signals; the human flourishes at the end are inconsistent with the setup" score="0.55" /></span>\n', 'Input:\n<<<\nThis proposal aims to optimize stakeholder alignment while minimizing operational friction in cross-functional workflows — a comprehensive solution for modern enterprises.\n>>>\n>>>\nOutput:\n<span>This proposal aims to <span>optimize stakeholder alignment<annotation type="AI" why="\'optimizing alignment\' sounds meaningful but has no measurable outcome — corporate filler AI produces from business writing in its training data" score="0.8" /></span> while minimizing <span>operational friction in cross-functional workflows<annotation type="AI" why="three abstract nouns strung together that describe no specific problem or action" score="0.75" /></span> <span>—<annotation type="AI" why="em dash — almost never typed manually, AI uses it freely because it appears throughout its training data" score="0.7" /></span> <span>a comprehensive solution for modern enterprises<annotation type="AI" why="closes by promising everything to everyone — a sweeping claim AI makes because it sounds confident rather than because it means something" score="0.8" /></span>.<annotation type="AI" why="pure corporate jargon with no concrete claims, an em dash, and a sweeping universal claim" score="0.85" /></span>\n', 'Input:\n<<<\nHonestly, I changed my mind halfway thruogh, but then the second draft kind of worked.\n>>>\n>>>\nOutput:\n<span><span>Honestly<annotation type="human" why="\'Honestly\' at the start signals the person is about to admit something — a spoken register people use when being candid" score="0.7" /></span>, I changed <span>my mind<annotation type="human" why="changing one\'s mind is something that happened to a real person during a real process, not a rhetorical device" score="0.55" /></span> halfway thr<span>uo<annotation type="human" why="typo from fast typing" score="0.9" /></span>gh, but then the second draft <span>kind of<annotation type="human" why="\'kind of worked\' is an honest admission of partial success from someone still unsure — not a clean resolution" score="0.75" /></span> worked.<annotation type="human" why="candid register, a typo, and partial success language all signal a real person reflecting on their work" score="0.8" /></span>\n', 'Input:\n<<<\nTo ensure fairness, transparency, and accountability, we adopt an principled evaluation framework for all outcomes.\n>>>\n>>>\nOutput:\n<span>To ensure <span>fairness, transparency, and accountability<annotation type="AI" why="a fixed trio of values that appears together across policy and compliance writing — AI reaches for this combination automatically" score="0.8" /></span>, we adopt <span>an<annotation type="human" why="grammatical error — \'an\' before a consonant, the kind of mistake a human makes" score="0.7" /></span> <span>principled evaluation framework for all outcomes<annotation type="AI" why="commits to a rigorous framework without naming a single principle or defining what \'all outcomes\' means" score="0.7" /></span>.<annotation type="AI" why="AI policy boilerplate with a grammatical slip that would not appear in a polished model output" score="0.65" /></span>\n', 'Input:\n<<<\nThis documentary delves into the intricate tapestry of medieval trade routes, serving as a testament to how commerce fostered cultural exchange across civilizations.\n>>>\n>>>\nOutput:\n<span>This documentary <span>delves into<annotation type="AI" why="\'delve\' surged in AI-generated text after 2022 — it signals depth without describing any" score="0.85" /></span> the <span>intricate tapestry<annotation type="AI" why="\'intricate tapestry\' is one of the most overused AI phrases for suggesting complexity — it evokes texture without saying anything specific" score="0.9" /></span> of medieval trade routes, <span>serving as a testament to<annotation type="AI" why="AI avoids the direct \'is\' and reaches for \'serving as\' to make a simple claim sound grander" score="0.75" /></span> how commerce <span>fostered<annotation type="AI" why="\'fostered\' is another word AI heavily overuses when describing positive development or influence" score="0.7" /></span> cultural exchange across civilizations.<annotation type="AI" why="stacked AI vocabulary markers — \'delves\', \'intricate tapestry\', \'fostered\', \'serving as a testament\' — make this unmistakably AI-generated" score="0.9" /></span>\n', 'Input:\n<<<\nAda Lovelace wrote the first algorithm in 1843. The Victorian mathematician\'s insights were decades ahead of their time. The pioneering programmer has since become a symbol of women in computing.\n>>>\n>>>\nOutput:\n<span><span>Ada Lovelace<annotation type="human" why="names the person directly — the natural way to introduce someone" score="0.3" /></span> wrote the first algorithm in 1843. <span>The Victorian mathematician<annotation type="AI" why="AI was trained to avoid repeating names, so it rotates through descriptors — no human writer would call the same person by a new label every sentence" score="0.8" /></span>\'s insights were decades ahead of their time. <span>The pioneering programmer<annotation type="AI" why="a third label in three sentences — this systematic synonym cycling is an AI artifact of repetition-penalty training, not a stylistic choice" score="0.85" /></span> has since become a symbol of women in computing.<annotation type="AI" why="systematic name-rotation across three sentences is a signature AI pattern from repetition-penalty training" score="0.8" /></span>\n', 'Input:\n<<<\nanyway i told her it was fine and i meant it at the time but then i was in the car on the way home and i started crying which was stupid because it IS fine\n>>>\n>>>\nOutput:\n<span>anyway i told her <span>it was fine and i meant it at the time<annotation type="human" why="presenting a past emotional state as settled — sets up the contradiction that follows" score="0.7" /></span> but then i was in the car on the way home and <span>i started crying<annotation type="human" why="the feeling arrived later, on its own, without a trigger they chose — real emotional experience, not a constructed narrative" score="0.85" /></span> which was <span>stupid<annotation type="human" why="immediately judging their own reaction mid-sentence — people do this, AI does not interrupt itself to pass verdict on its own feelings" score="0.8" /></span> because it <span>IS<annotation type="human" why="the capitalized IS is an attempt to override the earlier crying — the emotional contradiction is visible in the punctuation" score="0.85" /></span> fine<annotation type="human" why="lowercase throughout with raw emotional contradiction and self-judgment — too messy and specific to be AI" score="0.9" /></span>\n']
